textBeforeTable: Western North Pacific names WMO tropical cyclones names web page South Atlantic Wellington - East of 160 °E and south of 25 °S (Fiji names used) Fiji - East of 160 °E and north of 25 °S Papua New Guinea - 141-160 °E and north of 10/12 °S Indonesia - South East Indian Ocean (90-125 °E, north of 10 °S) Australia - 90-160 °E, south of about 10 °S South-west Indian - West of 90 °E Southern hemisphere index North Indian North Atlantic Eastern North Pacific - East of 140 °W Central North Pacific - 140-180 °W Philippines - 5-25 °N 115-135 °E Western north Pacific - West of 180 °E Northern hemisphere index Note, not all tropical depressions reach tropical storm status or are given names. Southern hemisphere storms are numbered in a single sequence irrespective of whether they are in the "S" or "P" areas. North Indian Ocean storms are numbered in a single sequence irrespective of whether they are in the "A" or "B" areas. NHC Miami and CPHC Hawaii also use the "ATCF" identifier for Eastern & Central North Pacific and Atlantic depressions. For example, EP052012 indicates the 5th tropical depression in 2012 in the Eastern North Pacific.
textAfterTable: Since 2000 onwards, a new international list of names has been used for tropical storms in the North-West Pacific basin and are assigned by the Japan Meteorological Agency as storms develop. This version of the list includes names used since 2012.  The year is included in parentheses after the last name to be used in that season.
